TITLE: U.S. Job Market Eases, but Hiring Remains Firm
SUMMARY: Employers added 175,000 jobs in April, a milder pace than in the winter months, though layoffs have remained low and most sectors appear stable.

TITLE: The Fed Is Eyeing the Job Market, but It’s Difficult to Read
SUMMARY: Fed officials are watching labor trends as they contemplate when to cut rates. But different measures are telling different stories.

TITLE: North Carolina Triad Tries to Reinvent Its Economy
SUMMARY: North Carolina’s Triad was built on tobacco, textiles and furniture. Now it’s trying to forge a new economy from more highly skilled manufacturing.

TITLE: Job Openings and Hiring Are at a 3-Year Ebb
SUMMARY: March data showed a cooling labor market, but layoffs remain low. The overall trend is likely to be welcomed by Federal Reserve policymakers.

TITLE: The Fed Tries to Steer Clear of Politics, but an Election Year Is Making It Tough
SUMMARY: Economists are wondering whether political developments could play into both the Fed’s near-term decisions and its long-term independence.

TITLE: Fed Holds Rates Steady, Noting Lack of Progress on Inflation
SUMMARY: The Federal Reserve left interest rates unchanged for a sixth straight meeting and suggested that rates would stay high for longer.

TITLE: Federal Money Is All Over Milwaukee. Biden Hopes Voters Will Notice.
SUMMARY: White House officials have barnstormed Wisconsin to make the connection between big changes and their signature laws.

TITLE: He Won by a Landslide. Why Is He Fighting for His Political Life?
SUMMARY: Ben Houchen, a regional mayor in the north of England, faces a close re-election race, partly thanks to the broader troubles of Britain’s Conservative Party.

TITLE: Walmart Introduces a New Store Brand for ‘Quality Food’
SUMMARY: The Better Goods store brand will carry plant-based, gluten-free and higher-end food and could help the retailer attract more affluent shoppers.

TITLE: High Fed Rates Are Not Crushing Growth. Wealthier People Help Explain Why.
SUMMARY: High rates usually pull down asset prices and hurt the housing market. Those channels are muted now, possibly making policy slower to work.

TITLE: Inflation Is Stubborn. Is the Federal Budget Deficit Making It Worse?
SUMMARY: Economists are divided over whether the growing amount of federal borrowing is fueling demand and driving up prices.

TITLE: How High Wall Street Thinks the Fed Will Keep Interest Rates
SUMMARY: Stubborn inflation has led traders to forecast far fewer rate cuts by the Federal Reserve than just a few months ago.

TITLE: U.S. Economy Grew at 1.6% Rate in First-Quarter Slowdown
SUMMARY: Gross domestic product, adjusted for inflation, increased at a 1.6 percent annual rate in the first three months of the year.

TITLE: N.F.L. Draft Is Like Super Bowl for City of Detroit
SUMMARY: Places that are not usual sites for the league’s marquee game are jumping at the chance to be the host of its three-day draft.

TITLE: Blinken’s Visit to China: What to Know
SUMMARY: Secretary of State Antony J. Blinken is in China this week as tensions have risen over trade, security, Russia’s war on Ukraine and the Middle East crisis.

TITLE: Antony Blinken Visits China
SUMMARY: Tensions over economic ties are running high, threatening to disrupt a fragile cooperation between the U.S. and China.

TITLE: ‘Pay Later’ Lenders Have an Issue With Credit Bureaus
SUMMARY: Firms like Experian and TransUnion say it is time for “buy now, pay later” loans to appear on consumer credit reports. The lenders aren’t ready to sign on.

TITLE: Could the Union Victory at VW Set Off a Wave?
SUMMARY: Some experts say the outcome at a plant in Chattanooga, Tenn., may be organized labor’s most significant advance in decades. But the road could get rockier.

TITLE: A Bill to Limit Canada’s Trade Negotiators on Farm Goods Edges Nearer to Law
SUMMARY: The measure from a member of the Bloc Québécois would ban changes to the supply management system for dairy, poultry and eggs.

TITLE: VW Workers in Tennessee Vote to Join UAW Union
SUMMARY: The Volkswagen plant in Chattanooga is set to become the first unionized auto factory in the South not owned by one of Detroit’s Big Three.
